    <div class="column">
        <p>From first glance, I can tell that this series is special. And no, not because of how beautiful the art is, or how lovable the MC (Theo Fumis) and relatable his story is, and the one character that said the quote at the top of the page, Sedona Bleu.</p>

        <p>This story is yet another one that tackles the theme of literatures, but in the angle of libraries. A state being controlled by librarians, the effect of genocide (in the same vein as <i>Frieren</i>, but as prevalent as <i>Avatar: The Last Airbender</i>), and various characters and their dreams, and how they interact with each other in their struggle to achieve it.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="hidden part9 paragraph">
    <div class="images">
        <img src="https://m.media-amazon.com/images/I/91HFdJD3TYL._SL1500_.jpg" height="200" width="150"></img>
    </div>
    <div class="column">
        <p>Everyone has their own reason to be a professional librarian, or "Kafna" in this world. Societal pressure, a passing whim, a dream they have to give up in order to survive. It's fascinating to see so many characters depicted in multitude of ways, but none of them are truly villanious. Not the deadpan girl who hated being bested physically because she hated being a woman in her culture, and it limits her option. Nor the girl who grew up on traditional values that are so backward, even people around her noticed and give her a wide berth.</p>

        <p>Other than those exploration of characters, this manga also has gorgeous art, and lore that stretches centuries of civilization that spans multiple culture. It's truly a work of competent fantasy.</p>
    </div>
</div>

